Learning Goals

  • Read in and prepare the meteorological dataset
  • Create several graphs with different geoms() in ggplot2
  • Create a facet graph
  • Conduct some customizations to the graphs
  • Create a more detailed map using leaflet()

Lab Description

We will again work with the meteorological data presented in lecture.

The objective of the lab is to examine the association between weekly average dew point and wind speed in four regions of the US and by elevation.

Per Wikipedia: âThe dew point of a given body of air is the temperature to which it must be cooled to become saturated with water vapor. This temperature depends on the pressure and water content of the air.â

Again, feel free to supplement your knowledge of this dataset by checking out the data dictionary.

Steps

1. Read in the data

First download and then read in with data.table::fread()

if (!file.exists("met_all.gz"))
  download.file(
    url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/USCbiostats/data-science-data/master/02_met/met_all.gz",
    destfile = "met_all.gz",
    method   = "libcurl",
    timeout  = 60
    )
met <- data.table::fread("met_all.gz")

2. Prepare the data

  • Remove temperatures less than -17C
  • Make sure there are no missing data in the key variables coded as 9999, 999, etc
met[temp <= -17.0, temp := NA]
met[elev == 9999.0, elev := NA]
  • Generate a date variable using the functions as.Date() (hint: You will need the following to create a date paste(year, month, day, sep = "-")).
library(lubridate)
library(tidyverse)
met <- met %>%
mutate(date = as.Date(paste(year, month, day, sep = "-")))
  • Using the data.table::week function, keep the observations of the first week of the month.
met <- met %>%
mutate(weeks = data.table::week(date)) %>%
filter(weeks == min(weeks, na.rm =TRUE))
  • Compute the mean by station of the variables temp, rh, wind.sp, vis.dist, dew.point, lat, lon, and elev.
met_average <- met[,.(
  temp     = mean(temp,na.rm=TRUE),
  rh       = mean(rh,na.rm=TRUE),
  wind.sp  = mean(wind.sp,na.rm=TRUE),
  dew.point = mean(dew.point,na.rm=TRUE),
  vis.dist = mean(vis.dist,na.rm=TRUE),
  lat      = mean(lat),
  lon      = mean(lon), 
  elev     = mean(elev,na.rm=TRUE)
), by=c("USAFID", "day")]
  • Create a region variable for NW, SW, NE, SE based on lon = -98.00 and lat = 39.71 degrees
met_average <- met_average %>%
mutate(region = if_else(lon >= -98.00 & lat > 39.71, "NE", if_else(
lon <= -98.00 & lat > 39.71, "NW", if_else(
lon >= -98.00 & lat < 39.71, "SW", "SE"
))))
  • Create a categorical variable for elevation as in the lecture slides
met_average <- met_average %>%
mutate(elev_cat = if_else(elev > 252, "high", "low"))

3. Use geom_violin to examine the wind speed and dew point by region

You saw how to use geom_boxplot in class. Try using geom_violin instead (take a look at the help). (hint: You will need to set the x aesthetic to 1)

  • Use facets
  • Make sure to deal with NAs
  • Describe what you observe in the graph
met_average %>%
filter(!is.na(region)) %>%
ggplot() +
geom_violin(mapping = aes(x = 1, y = dew.point, fill = region)) +
facet_wrap(~ region, nrow = 2)

We can see somewhat normal distributions for the wind speed graphs with geom_violin. Throughout all regions, the speed data is, for the most part below 10m/s, with the highest averages around 5m/s. The Northeast region seems to have the highest outliar, nearing 17m/s, but all the regions of the United States seem to have consistent concentrations of speed.

As for dew point, there is no consistency. As oposed to wind speed, the tendency is overall on the higher side for this variable. We can see the Northeast and Southwest have the highest concentrations overall, while the Northwest is all over the place with dew point levels.

4. Use geom_jitter with stat_smooth to examine the association between dew point and wind speed by region

  • Color points by region
  • Make sure to deal with NAs
  • Fit a linear regression line by region
  • Describe what you observe in the graph
ggplot(data = met_average, mapping = aes(x= dew.point, y= wind.sp, color = region)) +
geom_point(alpha = 0.3, position = "jitter") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "black")

The graph shows clustering between the dew points and the wind speed. The regression line shows a slight negative correlation, though there does not seem to be any clear relationship between the four regionsâ wind speed and dew points.

5. Use geom_bar to create barplots of the weather stations by elevation category colored by region

  • Bars by elevation category using position="dodge"
  • Change colors from the default. Color by region using scale_fill_brewer see this
  • Create nice labels on the axes and add a title
  • Describe what you observe in the graph
  • Make sure to deal with NA values
met_average[!is.na(region)] |>
ggplot() + 
geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = elev_cat, fill = region), position = "dodge") +
scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Accent") + 
labs(x = "Elevation Category", y = "Weather Stations", title = "Weather Stations by Elevation Category in Different Regions")

The Northeast seems to have similar amounts of stations in different elevations, while the Nothwest has most of its stations at low elevation points. In fact, there are almost no stations in the lower elevation levels. A similar difference is seen in the Southwest, which occupies the majority of the weather stations, mostly in the low elevation category.

7. Make a map showing the spatial trend in relative humidity in the US

  • Make sure to remove NAs

  • Use leaflet()

  • Make a color palette with custom colors

  • Use addMarkers to include the top 10 places in relative humidity (hint: this will be useful rank(-rh) <= 10)

  • Add a legend

  • Describe the trend in RH across the US

library(leaflet)

met_avg2 <- met_average[!is.na(rh)]
met_avg2 <- met_avg2[,.(rh = mean(rh), lat = mean(lat), lon = mean(lon)),  by="USAFID"]

rh_pal <- colorNumeric(c('darkred', 'orange', 'yellow3'), domain=met_avg2$rh) 

topTen <-met_avg2[rank(-rh) <= 10]

leaflet(met_avg2) |>
 addProviderTiles('Stadia.Outdoors') |>
addCircles(lat = ~lat, 
           lng= ~lon,
           label = ~paste0(round(rh,2), 'rh'), 
           color = ~ rh_pal(rh), 
           opacity = 1, 
           fillOpacity = 1, 
           radius = 500) |>
addMarkers(lat = ~lat, 
           lng= ~lon,
           label = ~paste0(round(rh,2), 'rh'), 
                           data = topTen) |>
 addLegend('bottomleft', pal=rh_pal, values=met_avg2$rh,
 title='Relative Humidity', opacity=1)
